Auctions Report (WIP)

Jonas Gehrlein

7/26/2021

Introduction

The launch of the first rotation of parachain slot auctions on Kusama marked a major milestone in the development of the project and in achieving a scalable and decentralized future. It is exciting to see how many professional teams, many funded through the Web3 Grants Program (CHECK), were ready to launch and competed for one of the five ever available parachain slots. This post gives some background information on the candle auction, the crowdloan mechanism, crunches a lot of data (nothing too complicated though) and gives an outlook on potential future developments. In addition to the chain data with respect to crowdloan contributions, this post incorporates results from an anonymous survey that was conducted prior to the auctions (end of March / early April) with fifteen parachain teams (footnote: Note that the responses of the teams do serve as clear prediction for the future as strategies and situations are likely to change).

The responses in the survey indicated that many teams are ready to compete for the first slots on Kusama. 10 out of 15 teams indicated that they are aiming to bid for the first available slots on Kusama, while 80% stated that they plan their projects to be live on both networks (with 13.3% only on Kusama and 6.7% only on Polkadot). On a scale from 1-7, with an average of 6.5, teams indicated that they extensively thought about the parachain auctions and how to acquire a slot.

The Candle Auction: A refresher

Before continuing with the analysis of the individual auctions, it is a good idea to reiterate on the the auction mechanism. The candle auction is an old auction format from the around the 16th century where bidding was allowed until a literal candle went out. The uncertainty about the actual ending time of the auction was used to reduce auction sniping, which was already back then known to be an issue. This phenomenon describes the situation that bidders hold back their bids until the last possible moment to squeeze their bid in to not give other participants the chance to react. Many of us know that situation in online auctions such as eBay. The candle auction format was long forgotten but has proven that beneficial properties in the case of blockchain auctions (link samuel’s paper) for both avoiding sniping and XY and is therefore utilized to sell the parachain slots on Polkadot and Kusama. In contrast to the ancient candle auction, the end is determined retrospectively. That means, the auction always has a fixed length and only after it ended, a verified random function (VRF-LINK) determines the block that marks the end of the auction. We can mark four important checkpoints to describe the temporal procedure of a candle auction, described in block height. The following graph illustrates the process.

Start |—–(Starting Period)————| Start candle phase | –(Candle Phase)—–| termination block | —(Candle Phase)——–| End <- having a nice graphic here. The dots could be blocks and there are 4 specially colored blocks. The phases are span above it.

The start and end block of the auction determine the fixed length of each auction and give participants certainty about the temporal framework of the whole auction. The beginning of the auction is marked by exactly 27,000 blocks (around 45 hours) as grace period where both teams and users have time to prepare, because the auction has a zero percent probability to end there. After that, the start of the candle phase (or ending phase) marks when things are getting serious. Here, figuratively, the candle is lit and this phase lasts for 72’000 blocks (around 5 days). During the candle phase, the auction could end at any given block with equal probability (i.e., the candle phase has a uniform termination profile) (footnote: To reduce storage requirements, actually only every 20th block can be selected as the termination block). Bidding is allowed until the end of the auction. After the official end of the auction, a Verified Random Function (VRF LINK) draws the actual ending block (“termination block”) and implements the state of the auction at that block. Later bids are discarded and, in the case of crowdloans, contributions remain locked for the whole duration of the slot, but did not actually contribute to a higher bid. Therefore, the candle mechanism induces incentives to bid as early as possible (or at least shortly before the beginning of the candle phase) and thereby reduce sniping. For more information see WIKI and BLOGPOST.

Crowdloan Mechanism

Crowdloans are a novel way for projects to raise funds to buy the right to occupy one of the scarce parachain slots that the relay chain offers. In contrast previous funding methods commonly applied on Ethereum, this way is trustless and users can be certain that they receive back the funds at a predefined date. The actual costs of their contribution is hence the opportunity costs (e.g., the loss of staking rewards or the return from using funds differently). Crowdloans are programmed to raise funds for a specific team and have a very simple bidding strategy. First, the leasing periods that the crowdloan is bidding on is fixed and cannot be changed (in this rotation all crowdloans bid for leasing periods 13-20) and the bid is automatically increased exactly by the amount of a successful contribution (footnote: To decrease the storage requirements, those bids are actually only cast on-chain once the candle period starts). A crowdloan is therefore a vessel that funnels contributions automatically into bids. In the absence of manual bidders (i.e., not from crowdloans), contributions are identical to bids in the auctions.

Auction Schedule

In total, the first rotation auctioned off five available parachain slots during June and July 2021. The first auction started at the June 15th and the last auction ended on the July 20th. Each auction lasted seven days with a two day starting period and five days of candle period. Auction Data

Let us dive into the data. As mentioned before, all bids were cast by crowdloans (with a few non-serious manual bids, which are discarded from the analysis because of their irrelevance). This was to be expected as 86.7% of projects predicted that they’d use crowdloans to raise funding in the survey, while 2 projects indicated that they will be bidding with their own funds. Either they changed their strategy or we can expect some individual bidders in the next sequence of auctions. Most projects said their project requires operation of at least 1 year, which is why all crowdloans were programmed to bid for the entirety of 8 leasing periods (13-20).

Auction 1-3

From the very beginning, three strong teams crystallized and it was no surprise that they’d occupy the first three slots on Kusama. Karura (LINK), a DeFi focused project, took the lead from early on and surpassed all others teams by a large margin. Moonriver (LINK) which provides native Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) smart contracts on Kusama, started out lower than their competitors but was able to secure the second highest contributions before the candle phase started. Shiden (LINK), which also focuses on providing smart contract functionalities, secured the third spot. In total, Karura raised 501,891.3 KSM (USD 125,472,821). Moonriver raised 205,935 KSM (51,483,753 USD) and Shiden 138,458.2 KSM (34,614,541 USD).

The following graph illustrates the dynamics of the crowdloan contributions of those three projects on a daily basis. The vertical lines correspond to the ending dates of the respective auctions. As all bids were made for the full slot period and cast by crowdloans, they correspond to the bids themselves. After a crowdloan successfully won an auction, contributions are no longer allowed and therefore the curve flattens out for the winners.

Auction 4

In contrast to auction 1-3, the fourth auction had more action to it, especially in the pre-candle phase. Bifrost, a project that aims to provide liquidity for staked tokens, and Khala (LINK), a confidential cloud computing service, were head to head with switching winners periodically. The following graph illustrates the race.

As mentioned before, the winner constantly changed before the candle phase started (indicated by the first vertical line). However, Khala could secured their lead in all blocks with big contributions just before the candle period started. During the candle period, Bifrost was not able to catch up and therefore 100% of the blocks signaled Khala as the winning project of the fourth auction. Naturally, Bifrost was still in the race for the fifth and last slot after the end of the fourth auction (indicated by the second vertical line) and they kept gathering more contributions.

Auction 5

With a strong position from the fourth auction, Bifrost continued to compete for the last available slot. However, a project that only incepted their crowdloan a few thousand blocks before the start of the fourth auction turned out to be a strong competition for the fifth slot and promised a close call. Basilisk, WHAT THEY DO, got traction quickly. The following graph illustrates the head-to-head race between the two teams.

In contrast to the fourth auction, the pre-candle phase was not very interesting. But Basilisk managed to come very close to Bifrost with the start of the candle auction and the leading position there even switched from block to block. To get a better look on the details, we switch the resolution to the block-level. The vertical line illustrates the beginning of the candle phase.

We can see that Basilisk had a few situations where they could lead the winning bid. However, Bifrost’s position was too strong and they lead 96.6% of blocks during the candle phase. Given that each block has the same chance of being pivotal, this heavily favored Bifrost to be the winner, which actually was the case. Bifrost raised 136,817.8 KSM (34,204,449 USD).

The Impact of the Candle Mechanism

As explained in the introduction, the candle auction lasts a fixed period of time, while the actual winning bid is determined retrospectively. This leads to the situation, that, depening on the termination block, some contributions are still locked but do not contribute to a higher winning bid. In this rotation, this did not affect the outcome, but in future rounds it could be a decisive factor. The following table analyzes the contributions in more detail and splits those up into the different phases of the auction. It also shows the termination block and at which time (in % of the total candle phase) that the auction was terminated.

Name Pre-Candle Phase Candle Phase (Pre-Termination) Candle Phase (Post-Termination) Termination Time (in % of Candle Phase)
Karura 452,268.3 KSM 40,238.26 KSM 9,384.756 KSM 74%
Moonriver 158,898.2 KSM 17,586.75 KSM 29,450.09 KSM 47%
Shiden 102,039.6 KSM 34,984.62 KSM 1,433.891 KSM 79%
Khala 83,039.34 KSM 46,965.59 KSM 2,275.808 KSM 85%
Bifrost 90,543.84 KSM 45,516.78 KSM 757.179 KSM 97%

As mentioned before, the contributions of Post-Termination in the Candle Phase are still locked but did not contribute to a higher bid. Luckily, this did not affect the outcome of the respective auctions.

Future prospects

We are living in exciting times where crowdloans finally arrived to the Kusama (and soon) Polkadot network. With the inclusion of Parachains, a blockchain that scales becomes more closer. This marks a milestone in the development of the protocol and pushes us into the next level. The first five projects that are live on Kusama are Karura, Moonriver, Shiden, Khala and X. (Link to platforms). As we saw in the analysis, all projects funded themselves with crowdloans. With those devices, the incentives are a bit different for the team than we’d assume for bidders in an auction. The general assumption in auctions is that bidders want the good as cheap as possible. However, this might be different in the situation with crowdloans, because the projects do not (at least mostly) fund the slot by themselves. Even contrary to traditional auctions, the projects might even benefit from their higher bids, because it signals a higher value to the market and might increase the token price. Additionally, crowdloan contributors face trade-offs when contributing to projects. First, they are not doing so solely based on their preferences, because contributing to your favorite project which is predicted not to win, would waste opportuninty costs (both of unbonding time, and the time the tokens are locked in crowdloans). Additionally, they might want to get in the project as early as possible. At some point, one could expect that the token price gets diluted if more funds go into a project, but this depends on how the parachain teams structure the rewards. If they mint more tokens to satisfy the increased demand in crowdloans, the token price should fall with higher supply. If, however, the token pool to be distributed is fixed and left over tokens remain in circulation, price should rather increase with more contributors (as network effect increases and the project has more outreach).

Generally, we can expect that future auctions are much more dynamic. On the one hand, we might see projects that are in the “on-boarding” phase (like all of them were in those sequence of auctions) where the use of crowdloans is natural and of great benefit. However, after being active, projects might be in the “extension” phase where they need to win other slots to sustain their operation. In this case, crowdloans might not be the best tool. Also, they might not go all for the full period but try to “flick” together their timetable based on where they can score the cheapest slots. In a survey prior to the auctions, around 30% of participating projects suggested that they will switch to some private form of bidding (i.e., non-crowdloans) in the future. Public bidding might be also including smart-contracts where funds are gathered in the platform’s native token (maybe even from treasury). The former is similar to ICOs where project source funds from the crowd and offer platform benefits in exchange. However, this might change in the extension phase, where projects might utilize their own treasury or saving to extend the funds or fund with their own tokens. The reason being that it offers more flexibility (crowdloans are rather “dumb” and even overbid themselves and also it might get harder to provide platform rewards for new users. Additionally, with parachains, smart-contracts are possible and make it possible to source funds trustless while offering an interface for some more sophisticated bidding strategies. And it reduces the effort of conducting a crowdloan campaign. More flexible to jump into bidding for slots that are starting but might be cheaper. Overlapping explaining.
